    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-05-08T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-05-08T08:00:00-05:00" n="461"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d461">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">396.1 GE/5–854: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">United States Delegation</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-05-08T14:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 8, 1954—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 144. Repeated information Paris 223,
                    Saigon 42. <persName corresp="#p_NDK1">Dac Khe</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_BK1">Buu Kinh</persName> outlined views Vietnamese delegation
                    with which they said <persName corresp="#p_BD1">Bao Dai</persName> in general
                    agreement to Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_HDR1">Heath</persName> as follows: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Vietnam had never wanted Geneva conference. They hoped it would fail
                            though they would not sabotage it.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>They were somewhat concerned over US headlines (New York <hi
                                rend="italic">Herald Tribune</hi> May 7) we were “writing off”
                            Vietnam. Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_HDR1">Heath</persName> assured
                            them this not US intention.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Vietnamese feel most strongly military solution Indochina must be tied
                            to political solution and accordingly they fear French desire end war
                            will lead them accept cease-fire without political guarantees.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Vietnamese would support French proposal for armistice provided it was
                            part of a military political program; <persName corresp="#p_LJ1"
                                >Laniel</persName> plan acceptable basis but should be expanded
                            include <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> inspection teams along Chinese
                            border; Viet Minh should lay down arms under amnesty guaranteed by
                                <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>. Some time after armistice
                            national elections would occur followed then (and only then) in
                            coalition government if election results so dictated.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>Vietnamese plan discussed generally with French but without references
                                <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> which Vietnamese fear unacceptable
                            to French.</item>
                        <label>6.</label>
                        <item>Vietnamese believe Security Council safest <gloss target="#t_UN1"
                                >UN</gloss> form introduce their problems since the US or Chinese
                            Nationalist veto could block unacceptable Soviet proposal. They seemed
                            concerned re undesirable Indian leadership <gloss target="#t_UNGA1"
                                >UNGA</gloss>.</item>
                        <pb facs="0759" n="733" xml:id="pg_733"/>
                        <label>7.</label>
                        <item>On conference tactics, <persName corresp="#p_NDK1">Dac Khe</persName>
                            says Vietnamese desire speak after Viet Minh in order follows 24 hours
                            later with speech which would both rebut and attack while leaving
                            responsibility Viet Minh for throwing first stone.</item>
                        <label>8.</label>
                        <item>It was agreed US and Vietnamese delegations should maintain close
                            contact.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
